    15	and ``...::test_bootstrap_with_bus_reuses_existing_directory``.
    16	
    17	Why we picked KSM as the bus substrate
    18	--------------------------------------
    19	
    20	We considered three substrates before settling on KSM directory records:
    21	
    22	1. **Standalone Keeper records (one per message)** — would explode the
    23	   tenant's record count, blow past the 25k-records-per-app soft limit,
    24	   and lose ordering. Rejected.
    25	
    26	2. **External broker (Redis/SQS/etc.)** — adds a second auth surface,
    27	   second secrets-rotation story, and a second outage axis. The whole
    28	   point of the KSM bootstrap is that operators already trust the vault
    29	   for credentials; reusing it for low-volume agent coordination is
    30	   strictly less infrastructure. Selected.
    31	
    32	3. **Filesystem under ``~/.cursor-daybook-sync``** — works on a single
    33	   workstation, falls apart for cross-host agents and CI runners. The
    34	   daybook stays human-readable; the bus stays machine-coordinated.
    35	   Out of scope.
    36	
    37	Wire format
    38	-----------
    39	
    40	A single KSM record (the *directory record*, created on demand by
    41	``bootstrap_ksm_application(create_bus_directory=True)``) holds the bus
    42	state. Its custom fields encode messages as JSON envelopes::
    43	
    44	    {
    45	      "v": 1,                       # envelope version, monotonic
    46	      "id": "<uuid4>",              # message id, immutable
    47	      "from": "<agent-id>",         # producer label, free-form
    48	      "to": "<agent-id>|*",         # consumer label or broadcast
    49	      "subject": "<topic>",         # short routing key
    50	      "ts": "<ISO-8601 UTC>",       # producer wall clock
    51	      "payload": <json-value>,      # caller-supplied body
    52	      "ttl_s": <int>,               # optional, default 3600
    53	      "trace_id": "<uuid4>"         # optional, propagates across agents
    54	    }
    55	
    56	A separate custom field, ``cursor`` (single value, integer), is the
    57	high-watermark a consumer last acknowledged.
    58	
    59	Compare-and-swap (CAS) semantics
    60	--------------------------------
    61	
    62	The directory record is single-writer-at-a-time by convention; concurrent
    63	producers race in the open. We coordinate via the record's revision
    64	number returned from ``KSMCommand.update_record``. Each ``post`` /
    65	``ack`` operation:
    66	
    67	1. Loads the directory record and snapshots its revision.
    68	2. Applies the local mutation (append envelope, advance cursor).
    69	3. Issues an update with ``If-Match: <snapshot revision>``.
    70	4. On 409, reloads, re-applies, retries with bounded backoff (max 8
    71	   tries, total ≤ 12s — same rationale as the bootstrap verify loop).
    72	
    73	Producers MUST be idempotent on ``id`` so a retry after a partial
    74	visible-but-not-acked write doesn't duplicate. Consumers MUST treat the
    75	cursor as advisory and de-dup on ``id`` to absorb the same edge.
    76	
